      "alternativeRationale": "Engine places indirect retainer on the opposite side from the distal extension. The textbook clinical rule is geometric — perpendicular to the fulcrum line at its midpoint, on the side opposite the saddle. For most Class II cases these give the same answer, but in some configurations (Class II Mod 1 with diagonal fulcrum line) in practice the indirect is sometimes placed on the SAME side as the DE but at a perpendicular position to the fulcrum. In practice, instructors may also reuse an existing rest-only abutment (max anterior with ball/cingulum rest) as the dual-role indirect retainer rather than adding a separate one.",
      "rationale": "Indirect retainer placed perpendicular to the fulcrum line, as far from the axis of rotation as possible, to resist up-lifting of the distal extension base when masticatory forces displace the saddle apically (Lecture 5 p. 8-10). Standard locations: max canines for Class I/II, mand canines or first premolars for mand Class I/II.",
